                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.001C13/65: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Nuevo Laredo</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Boyce</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-06T21:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 6, 1929—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your December 4, 6 p.m. Last night Department sent an appropriate telegram to the
                    Governor of Texas with the view of having him take suitable steps to prevent any
                    interference with General Calles’ liberty and safety while traveling through
                    Texas. Governor has just replied that he feels certain that there are no charges
                    pending against General Calles and that no action will be taken by Valls to
                    arrest Calles or otherwise embarrass him.</p>
                <p>Please telegraph such comment as you may wish to make on Governor’s
                    statements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
